               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400302-name-504" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-504" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-504" type="surname" value="LYNDE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-504" type="given" value="ELLEN"></interp>ELLEN LYNDE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am wife of James Lynde, and am a milliner in the Lowther Arcade. The prisoner supplied me with goods from his masters, Staggs and Mantle, to the amount of 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. and 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 0<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I paid him 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. on the 1st of January, 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 0<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. on the 4th of January, and 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. in different payments—the last was on the 14th of February—I am sure I paid him all these sums.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROWE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you previously bought any articles of the prisoner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—the 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. was the first bill.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400302-name-505" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-505" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-505" type="surname" value="KERSEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-505" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN KERSEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am cashier to Messrs. George Staggs and his partner. The prisoner was in their employ up to the 14th of February—he has not accounted for either of these sums, which he ought to have done at the time they were paid him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did the prisoner do much in collecting? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not a great deal—not 50<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. in a month—they were chiefly small sums—I do not know his salary—I do not know that half his salary was to be laid by on every Saturday night, for him to receive it at the end of six months—I am not aware that he was in any pecuniary difficulties—he never told me he had a writ served on him—he left my master's service in February—it was a week before he was sent for by my master.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
